metadata.abstract: The study investigates the ordinary repertory of liturgical sources from Aquileia and Cividale, highlighting the significant German-Central European influence on their melodies. Through comparative analysis, it identifies distinct regional characteristics and orientations, contrasting them with other Italian and European sources. Despite methodological challenges and limitations in data reliability, the research underscores the intercultural nature of the Aquileian tradition and suggests further exploration of its unique liturgical identity.

It is frequently emphasized in the literature that besides indications of a connection between Aquileia and the neighboring Italian regions, the influence of the northern areas can be strongly felt. This may be attributed to several factors, the listing of which would exceed the limits of this paper. Suffice it to mention the intercultural position of this area, the fact that between the 11th and 13th centuries all patriarchs were of German origin or the influence of the Italian monasteries founded from here-so, etc. The many experiences referring to this influence served as a basis for the views of the local people, that research should concentrate on an identification of evidence of this German influence rather than the definition of an independent and, to a certain extent, imaginary Aquileian liturgy. And the evaluation of the sources requires several aspects other than the mere occurrence or absence of a certain melody. For example, my own research proved that distribution of the Curiale melodies in the sources, the assignment of them to certain feasts, the pairing of them, the compilation of cycles from them, and, last but not least, the actual variance of the melodies, all together outline a physiognomy of repertory that could be characteristic of a diocese or a consuetudo.

The other aspect I neglected here to associate with this study is the distribution of the melodies. The most important aspect to a certain extent is the chronology. As Camillo Oswald, among others, emphasizes, there is a not negligible difference between the 12th and 15th century state of the Aquileian tradition. Among my observations there may be cases where the differences are the consequences of chronological rather than geographical or institutional distance of the sources. However, the variables presented in the foregoing reveal the character of the Aquileian ordinary repertory, show its significant points, and are quite promising as to make the picture more accurate and convincing later on by examining the other aspects mentioned above. Thank you very much.
